{
  "id": "02-accusative-and-dative",
  "title": "Cases: Accusative & Dative",
  "description": "Use the accusative for direct objects and the dative for indirect objects, and learn how the articles change.",
  "estimated_minutes": 16,
  "cards": [
    {
      "id": "de-a2-den",
      "front": "den",
      "back": "the (masculine, accusative)",
      "notes": "*der* → **den** when the masculine noun is the direct object.",
      "tags": ["case", "accusative", "article"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-einen",
      "front": "einen",
      "back": "a / an (masculine, accusative)",
      "notes": "*ein* → **einen** in the accusative (masculine only).",
      "tags": ["case", "accusative", "article"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-dem",
      "front": "dem",
      "back": "the (masculine/neuter, dative)",
      "notes": "Dative marks the indirect object (the receiver).",
      "tags": ["case", "dative", "article"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-der-dat",
      "front": "der",
      "back": "the (feminine, dative)",
      "notes": "In the dative the feminine article is **der** (not die).",
      "tags": ["case", "dative", "article"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-fuer",
      "front": "für",
      "back": "for",
      "notes": "Always takes the **accusative**: *für den Mann*.",
      "tags": ["preposition", "accusative"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-mit",
      "front": "mit",
      "back": "with",
      "notes": "Always takes the **dative**: *mit dem Bus*.",
      "tags": ["preposition", "dative"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-ich-sehe-den-mann",
      "front": "Ich sehe den Mann.",
      "back": "I see the man.",
      "notes": "*den Mann* is the direct object → accusative.",
      "tags": ["accusative", "example"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-ich-gebe-dem-kind",
      "front": "Ich gebe dem Kind den Ball.",
      "back": "I give the child the ball.",
      "notes": "*dem Kind* (receiver) = dative; *den Ball* (thing given) = accusative.",
      "tags": ["dative", "accusative", "example"]
    },
    {
      "id": "de-a2-mit-dem-bus",
      "front": "mit dem Bus",
      "back": "by bus",
      "notes": "*mit* + dative. Literally \"with the bus\".",
      "tags": ["dative", "example"]
    }
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "l2-cases-theory",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Nominative, accusative, dative",
      "body": "# Three cases\n\nGerman marks a noun's **role** in the sentence by changing the article:\n\n- **Nominative** — the subject (who does it).\n- **Accusative** — the direct object (what is affected).\n- **Dative** — the indirect object (to/for whom).\n\n## Article table\n\n| Case | masc. | fem. | neut. |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nominative | der | die | das |\n| Accusative | **den** | die | das |\n| Dative | **dem** | **der** | **dem** |\n\nOnly the **masculine** article changes in the accusative (*der → den*).\n\n- **Ich sehe den Mann.** — I see the man. *(accusative)*\n- **Ich gebe dem Kind den Ball.** — I give the child the ball. *(dem = dative, den = accusative)*\n\n## Prepositions fix the case\n\n- **für** + accusative: *für den Mann*\n- **mit** + dative: *mit dem Bus*"
    },
    {
      "id": "l2-ex-match-cases",
      "type": "exercise",
      "theory_ref": "l2-cases-theory",
      "title": "Match articles to their case",
      "exercise": {
        "id": "l2-ex-match-cases",
        "type": "matching",
        "prompt": "Match each article form with its description.",
        "card_ids": ["de-a2-den", "de-a2-dem", "de-a2-der-dat"],
        "pairs": [
          {"left": "den", "right": "the (masc., accusative)"},
          {"left": "dem", "right": "the (masc./neut., dative)"},
          {"left": "der", "right": "the (fem., dative)"}
        ],
        "direction": "target_to_source"
      }
    },
    {
